' @id(USE-VALIDATE-CLI)
' @desc(USE-VALIDATE-CLI, "Run the structural validation gate deterministically from the CLI (`mdd validate`). The engine Project::validate() already implements the whole /mdd-validate checklist (id presence/uniqueness, per-side @ref resolution, trace-link + use-case->sequence integrity, source_link existence, the @sec contract) and is tested — but it had no command, so the /mdd-validate skill re-derived the checks by inspection (non-deterministic). This use case exposes the engine: `mdd validate` walks both sides and exits non-zero on a blocking structural error; `--json` emits a slim {ok,errors,warnings} machine shape the skill parses. Approvals, acceptance tests, and rendered-SVG gaps stay non-blocking readiness warnings. Realized by SEQ-VALIDATE-CLI; owned by CMP-VALIDATE-CLI.")
' Objective use case for cycle 0015: give the deterministic structural
' gate a real entry point so the skill stops re-deriving it by hand.
title MDD validate CLI — deterministic structural gate (objective)

left to right direction

actor "Developer / Agent" as Dev <<missing>>

rectangle "mdd toolchain" {
  usecase "Run the structural gate\nfrom the CLI\n(mdd validate)" as ValidateCli
  usecase "Emit a machine-readable\nverdict (--json)" as ValidateJson
}

Dev --> ValidateCli
Dev --> ValidateJson

ValidateCli ..> ValidateJson : <<extend>>

note bottom of ValidateCli
  Objective (USE-VALIDATE-CLI): `mdd validate` ->
  Project::validate() over both sides. Exit 0 when
  report.ok, non-zero on a blocking structural error.
  Warnings (approvals, tests, SVGs) never affect exit.
  Independent of `mdd review` — no chaining.
end note

note bottom of ValidateJson
  --json prints a slim {ok, errors, warnings} object
  (not the full registry) so the /mdd-validate skill
  parses a stable contract instead of scraping text.
end note
@enduml
